<header class="row container">
  <h1>Grid</h1>
  <p class="lead">We&rsquo;re using a folding compound grid for maximum flexibility in our responsive layouts. This is a fluid grid with flexible columns and fixed-width gutters to maintain proportional spacing and alignment for all screen dimensions.</p>
</header>

<section class="row container" id="howto">
  <h2>How to use</h2>
  <p>The concept is loosely based on <a href="http://www.jonikorpi.com/">Joni Korpi&rsquo;s</a> fabulous <a href="http://goldengridsystem.com/">Golden Grid System</a>.</p>
  <p>Unlike other grid frameworks, our grid system is not attached to css classes. Instead, they are set in SCSS using our simple grid varables. This keeps our markup clean and our layout much easier to modify at various breakpoints. You can even combine them to make interesting compound grids.</p>

  <p>In fact, we don't consider this system a framework at all. The only thing we've setup for you are the following grid variables and a couple classes for dividing page sections.</p>

  <h3>Default grid variables</h3>
  <pre class="language-scss"><code>   //Three Column Grid
    $c3: 100% / 3;
    //Four Column Grid
    $c4: 100% / 4;
    // Five Columns
    $c5: 100% / 5;
    //Six Column Grid
    $c6: 100% / 6;
    //Seven Column Grid
    $c7: 100% / 7;
    //Eight Column Grid
    $c8: 100% / 8;
    //Nine Column Grid
    $c9: 100% / 9;
    //Ten Column Grid
    $c10: 100% / 10;
    //Twelve Column Grid
    $c12: 100% / 12;
    //Sixteen Column Grid
    $c16: 100% / 16;</code></pre>

  <p><em>To specify a width of four columns of a six column grid ($c6 == 1 column of a 6-column grid), use the following:</em></p>

    <pre class="language-scss line-numbers"><code>    /* Create a 4-column object centered in a 6-column grid */
    .object{
      @include gutters; /* Applies gutter spacing to sides of object. */
      width:$c6*4; /* $c6 = 1 column of a 6-column grid. Mulitply by 4 to specify 4 columns wide. */
      margin-left:$c6*1; /* Moves object 1 column to the right. */
    }</code></pre>

  <p>By default, this grid would be from one edge of the browser to the other. Probably not ideal for most people. To give your page some margins, we have two classes to give you some structure and extra theming power:</p>

  <pre class="language-markup line-numbers"><code>    &lt;!-- If you don't need a unique background for your section,
    you can combine row and container classes --&gt;
    &lt;div class="row container"&gt;
      &lt;section class="object"&gt;
        &lt;!-- Content that aligns to the grid --&gt;
      &lt;/section&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;
    <!-- If you do need a unique background for your section, separate your row and container classes -->
    &lt;div class="row"&gt; &lt;!-- Apply background here --&gt;
      &lt;div class="container"&gt; &lt;!-- Contains grid --&gt;
        &lt;section class="object"&gt;
          &lt;!-- Content that aligns to the grid --&gt;
        &lt;/section&gt;
        &lt;section class="object2"&gt;
          &lt;!-- Content that aligns to the grid --&gt;
        &lt;/section&gt;
      &lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;/div&gt;</code></pre>

  <h2><code>.row</code></h2>
  <p>Our row classes are designed to stretch from one edge of your browser to the other so you can add background colors and full-bleed images. We also like to add some vertical padding for consistent white space between sections.</p>

  <p>We&rsquo;ve included a few background classes in <code>/source/scss/theme/_layout.scss</code> to give you some easy background variations for rows and other elements:</p>
</section>

