<section class="row container">
  <h2><code>.container</code></h2>
  <p>Container classes contain our grid and add vertical margins to our sections. You can add a max-width value to give your design a static width after a certain size, but we recommend sticking with a fully fluid system based on percentages:</p>

  <p>Define your page width by using the <code>$margin</code> variable. We usually set this with a percentage based on one of our smaller grid units. For example, the base margin of Live Wires is <code>$margin: 100% / 18</code> (which adds an extra column to either side of our 16 column grid).</p>

  <p>This is fine at small window sizes, but what about at wider sizes? Instead of adding a max-width, we just increase the <code>$margin</code> variable on our <code>.container</code> classes:</p>

    <pre class="language-scss line-numbers"><code>    /* Increase margins after a certain width */
    @media only screen and (min-width: $screenMedium) {
      .container {
        margin: 0 $margin * 2 /* Double the margin size to squeeze the main content. */
      }
    }</code></pre>

  <p class="more"><a href="#header">Top</a></p>
</section>

<section class="row container" id="resizing">
  <h2>Units &amp; resizing</h2>
  <hr>
  <p>Every single dimension in our project is defined using relative units. Aside from our grid units and margins, which use percentages, we use <a href="http://snook.ca/archives/html_and_css/font-size-with-rem">Rems</a>. When everything is set using rems, we can proportionally zoom the entire project simply by changing the font-size of our <code>&lt;html&gt;</code> element.</p>

  <h3>Example</h3>
  <pre class="language-scss line-numbers"><code>   // Our default font-size is 100%
    html {
      font-size: 100%;
    }

    // We can proportionally increase the size of the enire site
    // by simply increasing or decreasing the root font-size.
    @media only screen and (min-width: $screenSmall) {
      html {
        font-size: 105%; // Increases everything defined by rems by 5%.
      }
    }</code></pre>

    <p>To make it easy to work with rems, we've included a handy <code>rem()</code> function inspired by <a href="http://foundation.zurb.com">Foundation&rsquo;s</a> <code>rem-calc()</code>.</p>

    <h3>Examples</h3>
    <pre class="language-scss line-numbers"><code>    .object {
       // Here's a few ways you can use the rem() function
       padding: rem(24px); // Converts a px value to rems
       padding: rem(24); // You can even leave out the px suffix
       padding: rem(24 12); // And use with multiple shorthand values
       padding: rem($line $line/2) // Use the $line variable for consistent spacing & flexibility
    }</code></pre>

</section>

